WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.040
So, my name is Jay Campanell, I'm a 9th grader at the Liberal Arts and Sciences Academy,

00:00:13.040 --> 00:00:17.980
and this is my story of how I started using R through a school project.

00:00:17.980 --> 00:00:22.559
So I'm from Austin, Texas, and in Austin there are a lot of things that make us so Austin.

00:00:22.559 --> 00:00:27.480
And one of those things is our very passionate love towards tacos, and specifically breakfast

00:00:27.480 --> 00:00:28.559
tacos.

00:00:28.559 --> 00:00:33.880
We will constantly debate other people on who we think make the best breakfast tacos.

00:00:33.880 --> 00:00:38.560
So what if we could take a scientific approach to see who really makes the best breakfast

00:00:38.560 --> 00:00:40.119
tacos in Austin?

00:00:40.119 --> 00:00:45.759
So my solution to this question was the taco index, which was a way of objectively reviewing

00:00:45.759 --> 00:00:50.340
the different tacos in Austin by measuring them on their total weight, their weight without

00:00:50.340 --> 00:00:55.000
their tortillas, and the thickness of their tortillas.

00:00:55.000 --> 00:01:00.119
So like the procrastinator I am, I didn't start working on this until I absolutely had

00:01:00.119 --> 00:01:03.000
to, and that was my capstone project.

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:08.239
The only criteria was that my project had to help the community in some way, and I thought

00:01:08.239 --> 00:01:10.459
the taco index did that perfectly.

00:01:10.459 --> 00:01:15.879
So I started working on this as a book because it was inspired off the Shanghai Soup Dumpling

00:01:15.879 --> 00:01:20.480
Index that was a book, but the more I worked on that, the more I knew that that's not what

00:01:20.480 --> 00:01:21.800
I wanted to do.

00:01:21.800 --> 00:01:25.040
So I went to my mom and I asked her, what do you think I should do?

00:01:25.040 --> 00:01:31.440
And she told me to use R. So like the good son I am, I took her advice and used R. But

00:01:31.440 --> 00:01:36.519
I had very little idea on what R was and definitely not how to use it.

00:01:36.519 --> 00:01:40.440
The only exposure I had gotten to it was tagging along to the cities where R Studio Conference

00:01:40.440 --> 00:01:45.519
was with my parents and the trip to Harry Potter World with unlimited butter beer and

00:01:45.519 --> 00:01:48.440
extremely overpriced wands.

00:01:48.440 --> 00:01:49.760
So I was confused.

00:01:49.760 --> 00:01:51.639
I didn't know what to do.

00:01:52.480 --> 00:01:56.720
So like every R programmer, I went to Google and I searched what I needed to do.

00:01:56.720 --> 00:02:00.199
So I searched, how do I put a Google sheet in R?

00:02:00.199 --> 00:02:05.879
And I clicked on one of the first links, copy-pasted the code, and then tweaked it until it worked

00:02:05.879 --> 00:02:06.879
for me.

00:02:06.879 --> 00:02:12.279
And eventually, I got a blank Google sheet into R, and I thought that was pretty impressive

00:02:12.279 --> 00:02:13.479
for myself.

00:02:13.479 --> 00:02:17.960
So I had this blank Google sheet in, and now I just needed some data.

00:02:17.960 --> 00:02:22.559
So that's when we started going out and measuring the different tacos in Austin, specifically

00:02:22.559 --> 00:02:27.899
the Migas taco, because it was the breakfast taco of Austin.

00:02:27.899 --> 00:02:33.880
And we used tools like a scale and calipers to measure these tacos, which got many awkward

00:02:33.880 --> 00:02:36.199
and weird stares from other people.

00:02:36.199 --> 00:02:41.600
But we cut through the awkwardness, and eventually, we had our Google sheet full of data.

00:02:41.600 --> 00:02:44.080
So this was a school project.

00:02:44.080 --> 00:02:47.479
And at my school, the only tools available to us are Chromebooks.

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:51.080
And, of course, R and RStudio don't run on Chromebooks.

00:02:51.080 --> 00:02:57.440
So I had to work on this project through RStudio Cloud, and with the help of my mom and Google,

00:02:57.440 --> 00:03:01.520
we built the app up to where it is today.

00:03:01.520 --> 00:03:02.520
So this is it.

00:03:02.520 --> 00:03:05.800
This is the final product, tacoindex.com.

00:03:05.800 --> 00:03:12.960
And we use the graph to compare the different tacos based on the five different key points,

00:03:12.960 --> 00:03:16.699
and you can click and compare the different tacos there.

00:03:16.699 --> 00:03:22.619
You can also click and see a map list and profiles and about page of all the different

00:03:22.619 --> 00:03:25.300
places and tacos that we tried.

00:03:25.300 --> 00:03:30.940
So after completing this project, I no longer feel intimidated to just open R up and start

00:03:30.940 --> 00:03:34.139
working, and I've started to really enjoy it.

00:03:34.139 --> 00:03:39.259
But this project wouldn't have been anywhere as good as it was without the help and encouragement

00:03:39.259 --> 00:03:40.800
I got from my mom.

00:03:40.800 --> 00:03:45.419
So I hope all the parents here at least show their kids R, because maybe they'll love it

00:03:45.419 --> 00:03:47.419
as much as I do.

00:03:47.419 --> 00:03:50.220
And I'm excited to continue R in the future.

00:03:50.220 --> 00:03:51.220
Thank you very much.

00:03:51.220 --> 00:03:52.220
Thank you.

00:03:52.220 --> 00:03:52.220


